  "prompt": "Can I use Google images in my website?",
  "response": "Using Google Images directly on your website can lead to legal issues because images found on Google are often copyrighted material owned by someone else. Here are some important points to consider:\n\n1. **Copyright**: Most images on the internet are protected by copyright, which means you cannot use them without permission from the owner.\n\n2. **Usage Rights**: Some images are available under Creative Commons licenses or similar licenses that allow for usage, but you must check the specific license to ensure compliance regarding attribution, modifications, and commercial use.\n\n3. **Finding Images**: Instead of using Google Images, consider using websites that offer royalty-free images, such as:\n   - Unsplash\n   - Pexels\n   - Pixabay\n   - Shutterstock (for paid options)\n\n4. **Attribution**: If you do use an image that requires attribution, make sure to give credit according to the terms of the license.\n\n5. **Contacting Owners**: If you find a specific image you want to use, you can reach out to the copyright owner to request permission.\n\nIn summary, it's best to avoid using images from Google Images without proper permissions and instead source images from platforms that permit their use.",
